definition.value: Recognizes a phosphorylated epitope (S/T)P found in phosphoproteins such as MAP2, HSP70, cdc25, and DNA topoisomerase IIa, most of which are phosphorylated at the onset of mitosis. The number of phosphoproteins recognized by MPM-2 varies from species to species and with the cell type.

Raw sample measurements are normalized relative to positive and negative control samples with known activity and inactivity. Endpoints are usually expressed as percentage, which include percent activity, percent inhibition, etc.
Where control samples are not available, data can be normalized statistically assuming that the majority of the samples are negative, i.e. not active.  An example is z-score.
